These alternative medications may require a new prescription.
You should talk to your doctor or pharmacist about the best option.

These are FDA-approved medications that have the same active ingredient, strength, dosage form, and route of administration as your prescribed medication and therefore have the same therapeutic effect. In most cases, generic substitutions can be made by your pharmacist and do not require a new prescription.

Discretionary alternatives means replacing your prescribed medication with an FDA-approved medication that will treat you condition in the same or similiar way. Some alternatives may be a different dosage form or require a different route of administration. Discretionary alternatives require a new prescription from your provider.

Therapeutic alternatives means replacing your prescribed medication with an FDA-approved medication that has a similar therapeutic effect. Some alternatives may be a different dosage form or require a different route of administration. Therapeutic alternatives require a new prescription from your doctor.
